The '''France national under-21 football team''' ({{lang-fr|Equipe de France Espoirs}}), known in [[France]] as '''''Les Espoirs''''' ({{IPA-fr|És.pwaÊ}}, ''The Hopes''), is the national under-21 [[Football (soccer)|football]] team of [[France]] and is controlled by the [[French Football Federation]]. The team competes in the [[UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]], held every two years. The team is [[Coach (sport)|coached]] by former [[Toulouse FC|Toulouse]] manager [[Erick Mombaerts]] and was [[Captain (association football)|captained]] by [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] [[Defender (football)|defender]] [[Mamadou Sakho]] until his call-up to the [[France national football team|senior national team]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Espoirs: Erick Mombaerts |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/espoirs/der_sel_esp/cvjoueurs/527365.shtml |work=French Football Federation (FFF) |date= |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Sakho: "Je veux jouer la C1" |url=http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/breves2010/20100505_090145_sakho-je-veux-jouer-la-c1.html |work=France Football |date=5 May 2010 |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref>

Following the realignment of [[UEFA]]'s youth competitions in 1976, under-21 football teams in [[Europe]] were formed. The team is exclusively for football players that are age 21 or under at the start of the two-year campaign of the [[UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]] meaning a player can represent the national team until the age of 23. Since the coaching tenure of [[AimÃ© Jacquet]], there has been an unwritten rule among [[France national football team|senior national team]] coaches that players called up to the national team must have had prior international experience with the under-21 team. Due to the country's [[multicultural]] background, France regularly produces under-21 players who have gone on to play for other country's senior national teams. Players such as [[Mourad Meghni]], [[Issiar Dia]], [[SÃ©bastien Bassong]], and [[Hassan Yebda]] all represented France at under-21 level before opting to represent their country of origin at senior level.

France has won the UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship once in [[1988 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|1988]]. Notable players on the team that went on to play for the senior national team include [[Laurent Blanc]], [[Eric Cantona]], [[Franck SauzÃ©e]], and [[Jocelyn Angloma]], among others.<ref>{{cite news |title=1988: France sweep to final glory |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/Under21/history/season=1988/team/newsid=407048.html |work=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA) |date= |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> Blanc was named the tournament's Golden Player.<ref>{{cite news |title=1988: Laurent Blanc |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/Under21/history/season=1988/player/newsid=413119.html |work=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA) |date= |accessdate=12 July 2010}}</ref> The team's best finish since was in [[2002 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|2002]] when the team finished runner-up to the [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic]] in [[Switzerland]]. Though the 2002 team produced ten players who went on to play for the senior team, only one of them, [[Sidney Govou]], has become a regular international.

The France under-21 team does not have a permanent home. The team plays in [[stadium]]s located all around [[France]], particularly grounds of [[Ligue 2]] clubs. Because of the smaller demand compared to the senior national team, smaller facilities are used. Recently, the under-21 team has established the [[Stade Auguste-Delaune II]], home of [[Stade Reims]], as a home residence having played numerous matches there over the past two seasons.

==History==

Though, under-21 teams weren't formed until 1976, ''Les Espoirs'', a youth national team in France, had existed since 1950 playing its first match on 22 May 1952 defeating [[England national under-21 football team|England]] 7â1 at the [[Stade Jules Deschaseaux]] in [[Le Havre]]. The team's next match was two years later suffering a 3â1 defeat to [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy]] in [[Vicenza]]. For the rest of the decade, the youth team played seven more matches, which included a 1â1 draw with [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] in [[Budapest]] and a 2â0 loss to England in [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] in 1959. In the 1960s, ''Espoirs'' continued to play matches against fellow national youth sides. However, on 18 December 1968, the team contested a match against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria senior team]] in [[Algiers]] recording an impressive 5â2 victory. Four days later, the team draw 1â1 with the under-23 team of Algeria in [[Oran]]. On 12 February 1969, the ''Espoirs'' played the [[Hungary national football team|Hungary senior team]] at the [[Stade Gerland]] in Lyon. The match ended in a 2â2 draw.

